is, working as a private teacher to children of prominent families and at the Naval Academy, and as assistant to the founder of the St. Anne's Society. When she died of bronchial pneumonia on August 2, 1910 at 43, the Evening Capital ran a front-page obituary: 'She was a woman of high culture and deep learning and rare intellectuality.' In 1916 the St. Anne's Society installed a carved stone sedilia set in her memory — ceremonial seats for officiating clergy, still in the chancel of St. Anne's Church, Annapolis.","number":1}],"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Carrie Jennings Willcox","first_name":"Carrie","last_name":"Willcox","maiden_name":"Willcox","married_names":["Willcox"]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST114"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"carrie-willcox-1867"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM064","name":"Saint Anne's Cemetery","city":"Annapolis","county":"Anne Arundel County","state":"Maryland","country":"United States","lat":38.9784,"lng":-76.4922,"visitable":true,"hooker_connections":["HD2965","HD2966","HD2968","X02014"]},"institutionsById":{"INST114":{"id":"INST114","primary_name":"United States Naval Academy","name":"United States Naval Academy","alt_names":["Annapolis"],"type":"service academy","founding_year":1845,"location":{"city":"Annapolis","county":"Anne Arundel","state":"Maryland","country":"United States"},"primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Naval_Academy","wikipedia_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_Naval_Academy","primary_persons":[],"hooker_connected_people":["TD0141","TD0150","HD0880","HD1206","HD2382","HD2965","HD2966","HD2967","HD2968","HD3127","T01869","T01840","I00271","T01876","HD3335","I00300","TD0157","I00479","HD4101","HD4122","TD0242","I01138"],"person_ids":["X00855","X02014","X02091","X02359"],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":[],"sources":[],"notes":"Founded 1845 at Annapolis Maryland. Hooker-tree connections through Adm. George Dewey (TD0141, Acting Midshipman September 23, 1854, graduated June 18, 1858 fifth of fourteen; instructor 1868-1870; commanded USS Constitution as training ship 1867-1870; laid Memorial Chapel cornerstone June 1904) and his nephew Cdr. Theodore Gibbs Dewey (TD0150, graduate). Dewey Hall and Dewey Field at the Academy named for the Admiral. Significant beneficiary of George Goodwin Dewey's 1963 estate."}},"crossConnections":[]}